g so, she argues for the importance of differential embodiment and movement to the creation and survival of Black sociality, and refutes stereotypic notions of Africa as less progressive than the West in recognizing the rights of disabled people. Ultimately, this book foregrounds the engagement of diasporic Africans, who are still reeling from the violence of colonialism, slavery, poverty, and war, as they gesture toward a liberatory Black sociality by falling, floating, and flickering.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican diaspora. 0aDisability studies. 0aPeople with disabilities. 0aWomanism. 7aART / Performance.2bisacsh  aAfrican Diaspora.  aAfrican performance.  aBlack sociality.  aCripistemology.  aDifferential embodiment.  aDisability Studies.  aDisability and performance.  aDisability.  aEnfreakment.  aFungibility.  aHorizontality.  aIntersensorial.  aMovement.  aNeurocacophony.  aNeurodiversity.  aNon-normative.  aPerformance studies.  aPerformance.  aQueer theory books.  aQueer theory.  aSierra Leone.  aSpasm.  aThe black body.  aUnhinging.  adisabled people in Africa.  amotion.  aqueer performance art.40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479818488.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479818488423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479818488/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles